almohus,Sweden":"Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Zweden"},"en":{"abt 1050–":"about 1050–Deceased","1050–Male":"1050–Deceased","1052–Female":"1052–Deceased","1104–Male":"1104–Deceased","1015–Male":"1015–Deceased","1025–Female":"1025–Deceased","abt 1104":"about 1104","1104":"1104","1015":"1015","1025":"1025","abt 1050":"about 1050","1100":"1100","1054":"1054","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Sweden":"Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Sweden","Loddekopinge,Malmohus,Sweden":"Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kjeldsen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian and Danish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Kjeld</i>, a derivative of Old Norse <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’. Compare   Kelson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelson","meanings":["English: habitational name from Kelston (Somerset), derived from an Old English personal name <i>Calf</i> (genitive <i>Calfes</i>) or from Old English <i>calf</i> ‘calf’ (genitive <i>calfes</i>) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Alternatively, perhaps sometimes a habitational name from Kelstern (Lincolnshire), derived from the Old English personal name <i>Cægel</i> + Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’.","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish   Kjeldsen  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Keyle</i>, of uncertain origin."]}]},{"name":"Thott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Indian (Andhra Pradesh): Kappu (agrarian) name from Telugu <i>thota</i> meaning ‘grove’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357045,"age":4,"year":"1054","julianDay":2106026,"description":"Sweden and Denmark set boundaries.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1702072,"age":50,"year":"1100","julianDay":2122827,"title":"Vreta Abbey is First Christian Convent","description":"Vreta Abbey was established around 1100 and was the first Christian convent in Sweden. It was located in modern-day Linkoping Municipality. It was founded on orders of Pope Paschal II with large donations by King Inge the Elder and Queen Helena.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter Kjeldsen Thott I was born about 1050, in Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Sweden, his father, Kjeld Thordsen, was 37 and his mother, Mrs. Kjeld Thordsen, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Peder Kjeldsen Thott."},"et":{"abt 1050–":"umbes 1050–Surnud","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1052–Female":"1052–Surnud","1104–Male":"1104–Surnud","1015–Male":"1015–Surnud","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","abt 1104":"umbes 1104","1104":"1104","1015":"1015","1025":"1025","abt 1050":"umbes 1050","1100":"1100","1054":"1054","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Sweden":"Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Rootsi","Loddekopinge,Malmohus,Sweden":"Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Rootsi"},"fi":{"abt 1050–":"noin 1050–Kuollut","1050–Male":"1050–Kuollut","1052–Female":"1052–Kuollut","1104–Male":"1104–Kuollut","1015–Male":"101